function or IQ or anything.

00:12:12.930 --> 00:12:15.650 align:middle line:84%
In fact, in some cases,
it seems to get better.

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:17.441 align:middle line:84%
>>SHELDRAKE: Well, I'd
never heard of that.

00:12:17.441 --> 00:12:20.090 align:middle line:84%
But I'd heard of the so-called
split brain experiments that

00:12:20.090 --> 00:12:22.040 align:middle line:84%
were done in the
'60s, where they

00:12:22.040 --> 00:12:26.060 align:middle line:84%
severed the connection between
the two halves of the brain.

00:12:26.060 --> 00:12:31.190 align:middle line:84%
And the reason they did
it, to stop seizures.

00:12:31.190 --> 00:12:34.220 align:middle line:84%
The reason they went on doing
it is because most people

00:12:34.220 --> 00:12:36.460 align:middle line:90%
didn't notice the difference.

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:38.690 align:middle line:84%
The husbands and
wives of people who'd

00:12:38.690 --> 00:12:42.650 align:middle line:84%
had the two halves of their
brain completely separated

00:12:42.650 --> 00:12:45.950 align:middle line:84%
didn't notice any abnormal
behavior, which is amazing,

00:12:45.950 --> 00:12:48.562 align:middle line:84%
Isn't it, because we assume
that the coordination

00:12:48.562 --> 00:12:50.270 align:middle line:84%
of the right and left
halves of the brain

00:12:50.270 --> 00:12:51.830 align:middle line:90%
must go through nerves.

00:12:51.830 --> 00:12:53.600 align:middle line:84%
The fact that they
were coordinated-- they

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:56.540 align:middle line:84%
could still walk and move
normally and speak normally

00:12:56.540 --> 00:12:58.280 align:middle line:84%
and play the piano
normally, which

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:01.100 align:middle line:84%
must involve coordinating the
different sides of the body

00:13:01.100 --> 00:13:03.200 align:middle line:84%
and the different
sides of the brain.

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:06.380 align:middle line:84%
That rather suggests that the
coordination is not just based

00:13:06.380 --> 00:13:08.540 align:middle line:84%
on nerves, but
there's a field which

00:13:08.540 --> 00:13:11.420 align:middle line:84%
is working on and through
both halves of the brain

00:13:11.420 --> 00:13:13.770 align:middle line:90%
and unifying what's happening.

00:13:13.770 --> 00:13:17.210 align:middle line:84%
>>DAVID: Are you familiar
with hydroencephaly patients?

00:13:17.210 --> 00:13:22.220 align:middle line:84%
>>SHELDRAKE: Yes these cases
where people can have only 5%

00:13:22.220 --> 00:13:24.260 align:middle line:84%
of normal brain volume
as a result of being

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:26.090 align:middle line:90%
born with hydroencephaly.

00:13:26.090 --> 00:13:29.360 align:middle line:84%
There was a famous paper by
the British neuroscientist

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:32.840 align:middle line:84%
Lorber called, "Is Your
Brain Really Necessary."

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:35.240 align:middle line:90%
That was published in Science.

00:13:35.240 --> 00:13:38.460 align:middle line:84%
When he found perfectly normal
people who-- one of them

00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:40.910 align:middle line:84%
had got an IQ of
about 120 and had

00:13:40.910 --> 00:13:42.770 align:middle line:84%
got a first class
degree in mathematics

00:13:42.770 --> 00:13:44.420 align:middle line:90%
from Sheffield University.

00:13:44.420 --> 00:13:47.184 align:middle line:84%
And he got 5% of his
normal brain volume.

00:13:47.184 --> 00:13:49.100 align:middle line:84%
>>DAVID: And that means
that most of his brain

00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:50.960 align:middle line:90%
is just water?

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:53.310 align:middle line:84%
>>SHELDRAKE: Yes, it's
fluid, cerebrospinal fluid.

00:13:53.310 --> 00:13:54.110 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:56.450 align:middle line:84%
>>DAVID: And it's only
really like the size

00:13:56.450 --> 00:13:59.160 align:middle line:84%
of a strip of baloney around
the outside edge of his skull.

00:13:59.160 --> 00:13:59.960 align:middle line:90%
>>SHELDRAKE: Yes.

00:13:59.960 --> 00:14:01.750 align:middle line:84%
>>DAVID: The entire rest of
the interior is all water.

00:14:01.750 --> 00:14:03.125 align:middle line:84%
>>SHELDRAKE:
Totally astonishing.

00:14:03.125 --> 00:14:05.480 align:middle line:84%
>>DAVID: And just a little
spot above the spinal column.

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:06.900 align:middle line:84%
>>SHELDRAKE:
Totally astonishing.

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:11.720 align:middle line:84%
A recent case of a Chinese
woman who was found by a brain

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:13.880 align:middle line:84%
scan to have no
cerebellum, which

00:14:13.880 --> 00:14:16.730 align:middle line:84%
is the part of the brain
responsible for coordinating

00:14:16.730 --> 00:14:18.860 align:middle line:90%
movement and action.

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:20.480 align:middle line:84%
She was slightly
abnormal, but had

00:14:20.480 --> 00:14:24.420 align:middle line:84%
led a normal, functional
life until they-- well, she

00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:25.220 align:middle line:90%
still lives.

00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:27.350 align:middle line:84%
But they discovered
that she was totally

00:14:27.350 --> 00:14:30.200 align:middle line:84%
lacking what is considered an
essential part of the brain

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:33.210 align:middle line:84%
for coordination of
movement and balance.

00:14:33.210 --> 00:14:35.600 align:middle line:84%
>>DAVID: So how could
this guy get a degree

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:39.620 align:middle line:84%
from Sheffield University in
mathematics, and all he's got

00:14:39.620 --> 00:14:44.510 align:middle line:84%
is this little slice
of baloney for a brain?

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:46.010 align:middle line:90%
>>SHELDRAKE: Well, nobody knows.

00:14:46.010 --> 00:14:50.410 align:middle line:84%
I mean, what it tells us is that
standard views, that the brain

00:14:50.410 --> 00:14:53.930 align:middle line:84%
is the be all and end all of
consciousness and the mind,

00:14:53.930 --> 00:14:54.845 align:middle line:90%
is--

00:14:54.845 --> 00:14:56.990 align:middle line:84%
they're rather
exaggerated, those views,

00:14:56.990 --> 00:15:00.650 align:middle line:84%
that somehow, people can
adapt to having far less brain

00:15:00.650 --> 00:15:05.500 align:middle line:84%
tissue than normal and
yet get on perfectly well.

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:08.450 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, you see, it depends
how you think the mind works.

00:15:08.450 --> 00:15:11.270 align:middle line:84%
I think the mind works
through a system of fields

00:15:11.270 --> 00:15:14.900 align:middle line:84%
that are expressed through
the brain, rather than it all

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:17.000 align:middle line:90%
being just inside the brain.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.060 align:middle line:84%
And it's still remarkable
that so little brain

00:15:20.060 --> 00:15:25.700 align:middle line:84%
can result in somebody
who adapts to it in such

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:27.280 align:middle line:90%
a way they're fairly normal.

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:29.238 align:middle line:84%
>>DAVID: Well, when
someone is clinically dead,

00:15:29.238 --> 00:15:30.890 align:middle line:84%
